entry.title: Navigation from contextual menu should trigger automatic beacons.
entry.content:
Currently, if a user right clicks on a link and clicks "Open Link in New

Tab/Window", an automatic beacon will never be sent out because the user

activation state is not populated into

`begin_params_->initiator_activation_and_ad_status`. This CL modifies

the checks before calling `SendFencedFrameReportingBeaconInternal` to

check both the initiator activation/ad status as well as the current

user activation state of the initiator frame. The former will check for

top-level navigations from a direct click, while the latter will check

for top-level navigations from the right click contextual menu.



Since WPTs do not check browser behavior, a chrome/browser test is added

and this was also manually verified with the following steps:



1. Add debug logs to check that `FencedFrameReporter::SendReport` is

called.

2. Visit the following page to join an interest group:

https://cerulean-spiny-shrew.glitch.me/advertiser/travel.html

3. Visit the following page to load the ad with automatic reporting:

https://cerulean-spiny-shrew.glitch.me/publisher/index.html?iframe

4. Right click on the ad and click "Open Link in new Tab".

5. Check to see that `FencedFrameReporter::SendReport` was called.

entry.title: [DownloadBubble] Temporarily show the toolbar in immersive fullscreen
entry.content:
This makes the download bubble temporarily reveal the toolbar when it is

shown in immersive fullscreen mode on ChromeOS and Mac. On other

platforms and in non-immersive fullscreen, the behavior is unchanged

(there appears an "exclusive access bubble"/banner telling the user to

exit fullscreen to view their downloads).



Note that we cannot simply call BrowserView::FocusToolbar() because this

actually focuses the toolbar and the focus remains on the toolbar when

the download bubble closes, which we don't want. Thus, we need to

manually take out an ImmersiveRevealedLock so that the toolbar will

automatically hide when the download bubble closes.



This also fixes a bug where we were showing an exclusive access bubble

telling the user to exit fullscreen to view their downloads, when it was

impossible to exit fullscreen, such as in kiosk mode. And renames a bool

to a more accurate name.



Screencasts:

https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/15TyjGZ1-zxLZBg2sE2MVn6YLJiO0PC3I

formatting in `WPTExpectationsUpdater`. `update_versions(...)` has been

augmented with an "autotriage" feature that writes new expectations near

reflect new capabilities.

same line instead of relying on insertion order. There's no way to

order lines mapping to the same number without first committing the

more info at: go/noannounce and GAR criterion 1.3:

go/GAR-mobile#disruptive-announcements



By using the live region we are also providing the information to all

AccessibilityServices that may be interested in it, rather than making

an announcement that is TalkBack specific.

entry.title: [mojo] Fix multi-broker networks on Windows
entry.content:
Handle passing between a non-broker and a secondary broker in

multi-broker networks was broken on Windows. This change fixes it.



The fix is specifically for this scenario:



- a broker X is connected to another broker Y

- X has a handle to Y's process; but Y has no handle to X's

- X is the broker for (+ has a process handle for) non-broker Z

- Y and Z require an introduction

- X gives Y a transport for Z, including Z's process handle



The bug is that because Y doesn't have a process handle for X,

it will ignore *all* process handles sent by X, including the

process handle for Z. As a result neither Y nor Z will have

the other's process handle, and at least one must have the

other's process handle in order for other handles to be

transmissible between them.



The fix is simply to remove the unnecessary constraint, as it

appears to provide no security value: it doesn't matter if Y

has no process handle for X. It can still accept handles to

other processes from X.

entry.title: Update WaylandEventSource::touch_points_::window after wl_data_device::enter
entry.content:
For both pointer and touch driven window dragging operations, whenever

a `wl_data_device::enter` event is emitted by the server, ozone/wayland

sets the `target window` of this wl event as `focused`.



By the time ozone/wayland will finally dispatch the event to chrome's

event machinery, it also defines a `target` and the `location` for the

ui::Event itself.



For the case of touch events,

WaylandEventSource::SetTouchTargetAndDispatchTouchEvent() is used,

and the ui::Event target is obtained directly from |touch_points_|.

Later, in WaylandEventSource::SetTargetAndDispatchTouchEvent(), the

event position is also calculated, based on this event target

set previously (see ::SetRootLocation()).



The problem is that the ui::Event target could be wrong, making

attach/snap dragging windows operations fail if the target window

was different than its origin window.

This is because the |touch_points_| above was providing a wrong

target for the event, after wl_data_device::enter.



This CL fixes it by adapting the touch_points_'s window, whenever

WaylandEventSource::OnTouchFocusChanged() is called.

entry.title: Fenced frames: Event reporting support for ad component urn iframes.
entry.content:
Modify GetFencedFrameProperties to take in a boolean argument, which

allows clients to obtain the fenced frame properties associated with

the frame itself. This is useful when the frame invokes event

reporting APIs as the reporting metadata should be retrieved from the

frame itself. Without this change, ad component urn iframes nested in

the main ad fenced frame will use the fenced frame's

FencedFrameProperties for event reporting, which is incorrect.



Note for some other use cases, the FencedFrameProperties should still

come from the parent frame (the existing behavior), for example:

1. Non-ad-component iframes nested in a fenced frame, the

FencedFrameProperties from the fenced frame is used for event

reporting from the nested iframe.

2. Urn iframe nested in fenced frame, for shared storage, the urn

iframe should use the fenced frame's FF properties's partition. (this

has not been implemented yet.)



This CL also parameterized the test case so that it tests the

following cases:

1. Ad in fenced frame, ad component in a nested fenced frame.

2. Ad in fenced frame, ad component in a nested iframe.

3. Ad in iframe, ad component in a nested fenced frame.

4. Ad in iframe, ad component in a nested iframe.

entry.title: [//viz] s/plane/mailbox in entities involved in CopyOutputNV12() flow
entry.content:
The flow around CopyOutputNV12() currently makes the assumption that a

single mailbox == a single plane throughout. This is reflected in the

usage of "plane" and "Plane" in the naming throughout this flow.



In preparation for introducing handling of NV12_MULTIPLANE in this flow,

this CL performs renames to decouple "mailbox" from "plane". This will

allow for smoothly introducing a variant of the flow that processes one

mailbox for all of the planes. The renames are the following:



PlaneAccessData -> MailboxAccessData

plane_access_datas -> mailbox_access_datas

NV12SinglePlaneReadyContext -> NV12SingleMailboxReadyContext

entry.title: [AboutThisSite] Fix heap use after free & links opening on wrong window
entry.content:
The ATS was using BrowserView to deal with the events of the

ATSSidePanel WebContents, i.e. it redirects to the browser clicks on

links and mouse events on the SidePanel's diner webpage. However, the

BrowserView associated with a tab can change if a tab is moved to

another window.



In this CL, we make ATSSidePanel depend directly on the tab's

WebContents instead of the BrowserView associated with the tab's

WebContents at the creation moment of the ATSSidePanel. The tab's web

contents will remain the same for the lifetime of the ATSSidePanelView

and we can fetch the correct BrowserView when an event related to the

side panel's WebContents occurs.

entry.content:
This change sets a drop effect to “none” when a CSE item is dragged

away from the Drive. This results in a small red icon at the corner of

the dragged object, which hints the user that the operation is not

possible.



The automatic test for this behavior is left as a follow-up as there

are limitations on what one can do with artifically-made drag-n-drop

events.
